03881nam a22005535i 9780226135113DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013043357  a97802261351137 a10.7208/97802261351132doi  a(DE-B1597)568225  a(OCoLC)1233040882  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aDS79.767.C37bG55 2014 4aDS79.767.C37bG55 2014 7aPHO0000002bisacsh04a956.7044/362231 aGilbertson, Ashley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBedrooms of the Fallen /cAshley Gilbertson. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (144 p.) :b40 duotones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tBedrooms of the Fallen -- tAbsences -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor more than a decade, the United States has been fighting wars so far from the public eye as to risk being forgotten, the struggles and sacrifices of its volunteer soldiers almost ignored. Photographer and writer Ashley Gilbertson has been working to prevent that. His dramatic photographs of the Iraq war for the New York Times and his book Whiskey Tango Foxtrot took readers into the mayhem of Baghdad, Ramadi, Samarra, and Fallujah. But with Bedrooms of the Fallen, Gilbertson reminds us that the wars in Afghanistan and Iraq have also reached deep into homes far from the noise of battle, down quiet streets and country roads—the homes of family and friends who bear their grief out of view. The book’s wide-format black-and-white images depict the bedrooms of forty fallen soldiers—the equivalent of a single platoon—from the United States, Canada, and several European nations. Left intact by families of the deceased, the bedrooms are a heartbreaking reminder of lives cut short: we see high school diplomas and pictures from prom, sports medals and souvenirs, and markers of the idealism that carried them to war, like images of the Twin Towers and Osama Bin Laden. A moving essay by Gilbertson describes his encounters with the families who preserve these private memorials to their loved ones, and shares what he has learned from them about war and loss. Bedrooms of the Fallen is a masterpiece of documentary photography, and an unforgettable reckoning with the human cost of war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAfghan War, 2001-xCasualtiesvPictorial works. 0aIraq War, 2003-2011xCasualtiesvPictorial works. 7aPhotography / General.2bisacsh1 aGilbertson, Ashley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGourevitch, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGourevitch, Philip.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226135113423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226135113.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles